  "prompt": "How do I turn a regular microphone into a film-worthy recording microphone?",
  "response": "To improve a regular microphone for film-quality recording, consider these steps:\n\n1. Use a Shock Mount\n- Reduces vibration and handling noise\n- Helps isolate microphone from physical movements\n\n2. Add a Windscreen/Pop Filter\n- Reduces wind noise and plosive sounds\n- Improves audio clarity\n- Helps prevent harsh \"p\" and \"b\" sounds\n\n3. Improve Acoustics\n- Record in quiet, sound-treated rooms\n- Use sound blankets or acoustic panels\n- Minimize background noise\n\n4. Use an Audio Interface\n- Converts analog sound to digital\n- Provides cleaner, higher-quality sound\n- Allows better gain and volume control\n\n5. Consider External Preamp\n- Boosts microphone signal\n- Adds warmth and clarity to sound\n- Reduces noise floor\n\n6. Proper Mic Placement\n- Position mic correctly relative to sound source\n- Use mic stand for consistent positioning\n- Maintain proper distance from speaker\n\n7. Additional Equipment\n- XLR cables for professional connection\n- Phantom power for condenser microphones\n- Potential upgrade to a higher-quality condenser mic\n\n8. Audio Post-Processing\n- Use software like Audacity or Adobe Audition\n- Apply noise reduction\n- Equalize and compress audio",
